  "diary": "Woke up to grey skies and that familiar drizzle. Made my espresso at home—nothing beats that quiet moment before the day gets loud. The SR-520 closure meant I took I-90 instead, which wasn't ideal but at least predictable. Got to Remedy early to open up. Trained the new barista on grinder maintenance, which felt good; she's getting there. Mid-morning the espresso machine threw a fit, naturally, but we worked through it. Lunch was rushed—toast with avocado between register rings, the usual. Afternoon was calmer, which I needed. The rain finally stopped on my drive home. Quick stop at QFC, then a simple dinner of aglio e olio. Spent the evening with my camera gear spread across the dining table, editing those alley shots from yesterday. There's something about reviewing frames in the quiet of your own space that settles you. Tea, a photography book, some expense notes. By the time I hit bed, the day felt complete—not perfect, but solid.",
  "thought_process": "Today was one of those days where routine anchored me. The weather and the bridge closure could've derailed things, but I leaned into what I could control—getting to Remedy early, staying present with the new barista, solving the grinder issue without stress. I chose the safer I-90 route without overthinking it. Lunch was functional because I knew the afternoon would be better. The real shift came when I got home and touched my camera work. That's where my mind actually lives, I think. The barista work pays bills and keeps me sharp with people, but editing those frames—that's when I felt the day click into place. I didn't push myself hard; I let the evening be slow and intentional. Sometimes that's what a grey Tuesday needs.",
